# Import lobster data

lobster_abundance <- read_csv(here::here("data", "lobster_abundance.csv"),
                              na = "-99999") %>% 
  clean_names()
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   DATE = col_character(),
##   SITE = col_character(),
##   TRANSECT = col_double(),
##   REPLICATE = col_character(),
##   SIZE_MM = col_double(),
##   LOBSTER_COUNT = col_double()
## )

use the dplyr::uncount() function to expand a frequency variable

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Yay! Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format. Now let’s look at this a bunch of ways

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site, ), width = 0.2) +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_violin(aes(color = site, fill = site)) +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  facet_wrap(~ site, scales = "free")# scales = "free" will change the y axis scale per facet. 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(sample = size_mm)) +
  geom_qq(size = 0.2) +
  facet_wrap(~ site, scales = "free")
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_qq).
